      "content": "I understand your frustration and desire for quick relief; however, chronic kidney damage from a short-term vitamin D \"loading dose\" at such high levels has been reported in medical literature. Even if these cases occurred over extended periods of treatment rather than just two weeks, it still indicates that such high doses are not without risk. Additionally, vitamin D excess behaves similarly to toxicity, where your body's ability to detoxify isn't always a factor of time. This can contribute to calcium deposits and other harmful effects not immediately apparent. Your body cannot be expected to \"handle\" a spike that far exceeds standard supplementation guidelines. If your vitamin D levels are critically low, it would be prudent to take a measured approach, perhaps within the health professional's purview, rather than risking potential harm with unlicensed self-medication.",
